==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Swart
<hw>Swart</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>swart</ets>,
AS. <ets>sweart</ets> black; akin to OFries, OS. & LG. <ets>swart</ets>,
D. <ets>zwart</ets>, G. <ets>schwartz</ets>, OHG. <ets>swarz</ets>,
Icel. <ets>svarir</ets>, Sw. <ets>svart</ets>, Dan. <ets>sort</ets>,
Goth. <ets>swarts</ets>; cf. L. <ets>sordes</ets> dirt,
<ets>sordere</ets> to be dirty. Cf. <er>Sordid</er>,
<er>Surd</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of a dark hue; moderately black;
swarthy; tawny.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Swart</xex> attendants.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Trench.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Swart</xex> savage maids.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Hawthorne.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A nation strange, with visage <qex>swart</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Gloomy; malignant.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Swart star</b></col>, <cd>the Dog Star; -- so called from
its appearing during the hot weather of summer, which makes swart the
countenance.</cd> <mark>[R.]</mark> <au>Milton.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swart</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Swart
<hw>Swart</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make swart or tawny; <as>as, to
<ex>swart</ex> a living part</as>.</def> <rj><au>Sir T.
Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

